Reflection:




🔍 1. Pipeline vs End-to-End Model

A key insight from this project is the trade-off between modular pipelines and end-to-end multimodal learning:

Pipeline (ASR → Translation)
More stable
Easier to debug
Benefits from pretrained specialization
BUT: error propagation is severe
End-to-End (your model)
Learns direct mapping from speech → text
Avoids intermediate transcription errors
BUT:
Requires significantly more data
Harder to optimize
Observed instability (BLEU ~0.47)




🔊 2. Impact of Noisy Transcripts

From your results:

BLEU (clean): 0.47
BLEU (noisy): 0.37

This reveals:

Model is moderately robust to noise
BUT:
WER = 1.00 → very high error rate
chrF low → poor character-level accuracy
Key Insight:

Noise impacts alignment more than semantics




📊 3. Performance Insights
Length-Based Performance
Long sentences → BEST performance (BLEU ~0.66)
Short sentences → WORST

👉 Reason:

Transformer benefits from context richness
Rare Vocabulary
High rare words → lower BLEU

👉 Model struggles with:

Domain-specific terminology
Low-frequency tokens




⚖️ 4. Multimodal vs Single Modality
What worked:
Audio + text fusion improves contextual grounding
What didn’t:
Fusion adds complexity without enough data

👉 Compared to baselines:

Tabular/Text-only models: very high accuracy (0.99)
Multimodal model: harder to train + unstable
Key Conclusion:

Multimodal ≠ better by default
It becomes powerful only at scale




🚧 5. What Limited Performance
Critical bottlenecks:
Small dataset (~2K samples)
Limited training epochs
Weak alignment between audio + text
No pretraining for fusion layer
Decoder mismatch (MBart expects text-like embeddings)




